{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501152"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:24:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:24:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1726"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1726"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.43,0.09,0.19,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1726"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40231"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1726"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1726"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24924"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30260"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40231"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is brought in by ambulance following a trauma suffered to the skull from a hammer. She was assaulted in an attempted home robbery. The Glasgow coma score on admission was 10. A CT head shows a depressed skull fracture with minimal intra-parenchymal injury. She underwent surgical reduction of the fracture and was transferred to the high dependency unit post-operatively. She has no past medical history and is on no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate to provide post-operatively?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prophylactic hypothermia","Seizure prophylaxis","Prolonged prophylactic hyperventilation","High dose methylprednisolone","Hyperosmolar therapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeizure prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E - Traumatic brain injuries can be associated with the risk of subsequent seizures. Post-traumatic seizures can occur both in the early period (up to a week post-injury) and late period (after a week post-injury). The patient has risk factors for developing early PTS: Glasgow Coma Scale \u0026lt;/= 10, depressed skull fracture and penetrating head injury.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent guidelines recommend that patients with traumatic brain injury be provided with seizure prophylaxis; patients typically receive a prophylactic course of levetiracetam or phenytoin for 7 days. Although there is insufficient evidence supporting any one anti-epileptic drug, levetiracetam has a favourable risk-benefit profile, and its therefore commonly the drug of choice over phenytoin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic hypothermia - \u003C/strong\u003Ethere is a lack of evidence indicating that the usage of prophylactic hypothermia after traumatic brain injury can improve outcomes, and is hence currently not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged prophylactic hyperventilation \u003C/strong\u003E- there is a lack of evidence indicating that prophylactic hyperventilation therapy helps in improving outcomes, and can instead be detrimental in the first 24 hours after injury because cerebral blood flow is lowered during this time period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh dose methylprednisolone \u003C/strong\u003E- high dose methylprednisolone has not been shown to improve outcomes immediately after a traumatic brain injury, and has instead been linked to worse outcomes in cases of severe brain injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperosmolar therapy\u003C/strong\u003E - hyperosmolar therapy (mannitol and hypertonic saline) can be effective for treating raised intra-cranial pressure. As neither therapy has been shown to improve outcomes, rather than using hyperosmolar therapy routinely post-operatively, these agents are reserved for brain injured patients with raised intra-cranial pressure. In the case above, there is no mention of raised intra-cranial pressure in the stem, so this treatment would not be routinely used post-operatively.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Based on most up to date evidence, in setting of head injuries, the recommendation is to give treatment for seizure prophylaxis with either levetiracetam or phenytoin."],"references":["Torbic H, Forni A, Anger K, Degrado J, Greenwood B. Use of antiepileptics for seizure prophylaxis after traumatic brain injury. American Journal of Health-System Pharmacy. 2013;70(9):759-766.","Temkin N. Prophylactic Anticonvulsants After Neurosurgery. Epilepsy Currents. 2002;2(4):105-107.","Bakr A, Belli A. A systematic review of levetiracetam versus phenytoin in the prevention of late post-traumatic seizures and survey of UK neurosurgical prescribing practice of antiepileptic medication in acute traumatic brain injury. Br J Neurosurg. 2018 Jun;32(3):237-244.","Piccenna L, Shears G, O\u0027Brien TJ. Management of post-traumatic epilepsy: An evidence review over the last 5 years and future directions. Epilepsia Open. 2017 Mar 17;2(2):123-144. doi: 10.1002/epi4.12049. PMID: 29588942; PMCID: PMC5719843.","Harris L, Hateley S, Tsang KT, Wilson M, Seemungal BM. Impact of anti-epileptic drug choice on discharge in acute traumatic brain injury patients. J Neurol. 2020 Jun;267(6):1774-1779. doi: 10.1007/s00415-020-09769-5. Epub 2020 Mar 4. PMID: 32130500; PMCID: PMC7293662.","Pingue, V., Mele, C., \u0026 Nardone, A. (2021). Post-traumatic seizures and antiepileptic therapy as predictors of the functional outcome in patients with traumatic brain injury. Scientific reports, 11(1), 4708.","Pingue, V., Mele, C., Biscuola, S., Nardone, A., Bagnato, S., \u0026 Franciotta, D. (2022). Impact of seizures and their prophylaxis with antiepileptic drugs on rehabilitation course of patients with traumatic or hemorrhagic brain injury. Frontiers in Neurology, 13, 1060008.","Brain Trauma Foundation (2016). Guidelines for the Management of Severe TBI, 4th Edition. Retrieved from: https://braintrauma.org/coma/guidelines/guidelines-for-the-management-of-severe-tbi-4th-ed"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24924"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1726"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24924"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-11-03T07:24:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-08T08:19:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1726"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40231"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","